  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering, including:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Monitoring unusual financial activity\n\n3. Compliance with anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- International anti-money laundering standards\n\n4. Implementation of internal control systems\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Risk assessment procedures\n- Staff training on money laundering detection\n\n5. Record-keeping requirements\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Documenting compliance efforts\n\n6. Potential penalties for non-compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal liability\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent criminals from using financial systems to disguise illegally obtained funds.",
